<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,153,1115]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,549,575]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Etymology</emphasis>
. This species is named in honour and memory of Dr Alexander “Sandy” Bilton Roy in recognition of his nearly twenty years of volunteer work devoted to the curation and cataloguing of spiders, mites, ticks and termites in the Australian National Insect Collection.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,153,1115]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,656,683]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Colloff, 2019" authorityName="Colloff" authorityYear="2019" box="[327,461,657,683]" class="Arachnida" family="Nosybeidae" genus="Topalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="royi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[327,461,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Topalia royi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[467,556,657,683]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[467,556,657,683]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be distinguished from other species in the genus by the following combination of characters: (1) the rostrum incised medially; (2) the anteromedial edges of lamellae separated; (3) the partly fused epimera 
<collectionCode box="[315,343,729,755]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">III</collectionCode>
and 
<collectionCode box="[396,427,729,755]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">IV</collectionCode>
; (4) the medially indented anterior notogastral margin; (4) the laterally-positioned humeral projections; (5) the cerotegument consisting of a network of large, deep, angular foveolae; (6) the epimeral setation 2-1-2-3.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,153,1115]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,837,863]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Colloff, 2019" authorityName="Colloff" authorityYear="2019" box="[325,464,837,863]" class="Arachnida" family="Nosybeidae" genus="Topalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="royi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[325,464,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Topalia royi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[474,566,837,863]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[474,566,837,863]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is morphologically most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Colloff, 2019" authorityName="Colloff" authorityYear="2019" box="[984,1195,837,863]" class="Arachnida" family="Nosybeidae" genus="Topalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caliginosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[984,1195,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Topalia caliginosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1205,1297,837,863]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1205,1297,837,863]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, as detailed above.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,153,1115]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Balogh &amp; Csiszar" authorityYear="1963" box="[199,284,909,935]" class="Arachnida" family="Nosybeidae" genus="Topalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,284,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Topalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 2 (
<bibRefCitation author="Hunt, G. S. &amp; Colloff, M. J. &amp; Dallwitz, M. &amp; Walter, D. E." box="[358,549,909,935]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" refId="ref20301" refString="Hunt, G. S., Colloff, M. J., Dallwitz, M. &amp; Walter, D. E. (1998) An Interactive Key to Oribatid Mites of Australia. CSIRO Publishing, Melbourne. [CD-ROM]" type="book" year="1998">
Hunt 
<emphasis box="[422,471,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">et al</emphasis>
., 1998
</bibRefCitation>
) was collected from the same location as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Colloff" authorityYear="2019" box="[1016,1088,910,935]" class="Arachnida" family="Nosybeidae" genus="Topalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="royi">
<emphasis box="[1016,1088,910,935]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">T. royi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(leaf litter, O’Reilly’s Rainforest Retreat, Lamington National Park, 
<collectingRegion box="[587,719,945,971]" country="Australia" name="Queensland" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Queensland</collectingRegion>
(
<geoCoordinate box="[735,825,945,971]" degrees="28" direction="south" minutes="14" orientation="latitude" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" precision="925" value="-28.233334">28º14’S</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[833,939,944,971]" degrees="153" direction="east" minutes="08" orientation="longitude" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" precision="925" value="153.13333">153º08’E</geoCoordinate>
) coll. R. Kitching) and I consider it to be 
<taxonomicName authority="Colloff, 2019" authorityName="Colloff" authorityYear="2019" class="Arachnida" family="Nosybeidae" genus="Topalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="royi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">T. royi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[203,296,981,1007]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[203,289,981,1007]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
They share the characteristic pattern of cerotegument, faint striae on the lamellar cusps, equal ratios of prodorsal length to total length, notogastral length to breadth, and the morphology of the bothridial setae (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1846,1871]" captionTargetBox="[227,1361,1049,1821]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[227,1361,1049,1821]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 9. Scanning electron micrographs of dorsal aspects of (a) Topalia sp. 1 and (b) Topalia royi sp. nov. (Topalia sp. 2) (from Hunt et al. 1998)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3353122/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Fig. 9b</figureCitation>
). When the figure of the dorsal aspect of 
<taxonomicName authority="Colloff, 2019" authorityName="Colloff" authorityYear="2019" box="[642,713,1054,1079]" class="Arachnida" family="Nosybeidae" genus="Topalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="royi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[642,713,1054,1079]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">T. royi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[719,806,1053,1079]" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is superimposed on the scanning electron micrograph of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Balogh &amp; Csiszar" authorityYear="1963" box="[151,236,1089,1115]" class="Arachnida" family="Nosybeidae" genus="Topalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,236,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="303">Topalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 2, it fits almost exactly the outline of the lamellae and notogaster.
</paragraph>
